Class AbstractVectorMappingFeatureProcessor

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.eng.aisp.processor.GenericCachingDataProcessor

  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Serializable, IFeatureProcessor<double[]>
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    DeltaFeatureProcessor, NormalizingFeatureProcessor

    public abstract class AbstractVectorMappingFeatureProcessor
extends AbstractCachingMultiFeatureProcessor<double[]>
implements IFeatureProcessor<double[]>
    Extends the super class to map an array of feature data to a new array feature data. Subclasses must implement map(IFeature[], double[][]) to map from one matrix of feature data to another matrix of feature data.
    Author:

      • applyImpl

        protected IFeatureGram<double[]> applyImpl(IFeatureGram<double[]> featureGram)
        Description copied from class: AbstractCachingMultiFeatureProcessor
        The actual implementation of the processing. This is only called when the result was not found in the cache. The return value will be cached for later use.
        Specified by:
        applyImpl in class AbstractCachingMultiFeatureProcessor<double[]>
        Parameters:
        features - array of IFeature
        Returns:
        a feature gram containing the processed features. May be the input if no processing is performed.

      • map

        protected abstract double[][] map(IFeature<double[]>[] features,
                                  double[][] featureData)
        Map the given array of double arrays to a new array of double arrays. The number of double arrays returned need not be the same as in the input, and the length of each double array can be different than the input.
        Parameters:
        features - The original features from which the data is extracted.
        featureData - the data extracted from the given features. Should NOT be modified.
        Returns:
        never null. May return the given featureData array in which case the features are not modified. May return a 0x0 matrix (new double[0][]) if the matrix of features could not be created (e.g., not enough data, etc).
